# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: core-foundation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:core-foundation/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] The most prevalent use of Core Foundation is for passing its own primitive types for data, including raw bytes, Unicode strings, numbers, calendar dates, and UUIDs, as well as collections such as arrays, sets, and dictionaries, to numerous macOS C routines, primarily those that are GUI-related.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Other parts of the API include utility routines and wrappers around existing APIs for ease of use.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Utility routines perform such actions as file system and network I/O through `CFReadStream`, `CFWriteStream`, and `CFURL` and endianness translation (Byte Order Utilities).
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Some examples of wrapper routines include those for Core Foundation's wrapper routines for Unix sockets, the CFSocket API.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Some types in Core Foundation are "toll-free bridged", or interchangeable with a simple cast, with those of their Foundation Kit counterparts.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] For example, one could create a `CFDictionaryRef` Core Foundation type, and then later simply use a standard C cast to convert it to its Objective-C counterpart, `NSDictionary *`, and then use the desired Objective-C methods on that object as one normally would.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Core Foundation has a plug-in model (CFPlugin) that is based on the Microsoft Component Object Model.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Apple used to release most of CF as an open-source project called CFLite that can be used to write cross-platform applications for macOS, Linux, and Windows.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] A third-party open-source implementation called OpenCFLite extends the Apple CFLite for building on 32-bit Windows and Linux environments.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] It is maintained by one of the WebKit developers, but was stalled by 2015.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] The karaoke platform KJams maintains a fork since 2017.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] This version, by its programmer David M.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] Cotter, supports 64-bit systems and has a CFNetwork implementation with LibreSSL-based TLS.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] A fork of OpenCFLite was created by Grant Erickson (an original collaborator with Brent Fulgham on the SourceForge version) in 2021 with a companion port of the `CFHost` portion of CFNetwork, as OpenCFNetwork.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] The Swift Corelib Foundation, a fallback version of the Foundation Kit for the Swift programming language for non-Apple platforms, contains a near-full version of the Core Foundation released under Apache License 2.0.
[src:core-foundation/core-foundation] GNUstep includes a version of the Core Foundation called "libs-corebase".
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C programs developed for non-Apple operating systems or that are not dependent on Apple's APIs may also be compiled for any platform supported by GNU, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or LLVM/Clang.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C source code "messaging/implementation" program files usually have `.m` filename extensions, while Objective-C "header/interface" files have `.h` extensions, the same as C header files.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C++ files are denoted with a `.mm` filename extension.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C was created mainly by Brad Cox and Tom Love in the early 1980s at their company Productivity Products International (PPI).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Leading up to the creation of their company, both had been introduced to Smalltalk while at ITT Corporation's Programming Technology Center in 1981.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The earliest work on Objective-C traces back to around then.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Cox was intrigued by problems of true reusability in software design and programming.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] He realized that a language like Smalltalk would be invaluable in building development environments for system developers at ITT.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] However, he and Tom Love also recognized that backward compatibility with C was critically important in ITT's telecom engineering milieu.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Cox began writing a pre-processor for C to add some of the abilities of Smalltalk.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] He soon had a working implementation of an object-oriented extension to the C language, which he named Object-Oriented Pre-Compiler (OOPC).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Love was hired by Schlumberger Research in 1982 and had the opportunity to acquire the first commercial copy of Smalltalk-80, which further influenced the development of their brainchild.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] To demonstrate that real progress could be made, Cox showed that making interchangeable software components really needed only a few practical changes to existing tools.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Specifically, they needed to support objects in a flexible manner, come supplied with a usable set of libraries, and allow for the code (and any resources needed by the code) to be bundled into one cross-platform format.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Love and Cox eventually formed PPI to commercialize their product.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] To avoid legal disputes with his previous employers, Cox reimplemented his compiler for the language, which was renamed "Objective-C".
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The company's main product line consisted of this compiler, along with class libraries intended to be used with it.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In 1986, Cox published the main description of Objective-C in its original form in the book *Object-Oriented Programming: An Evolutionary Approach*.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Although he was careful to explain that there is more to the problem of reusability than just what Objective-C provides, the language was often compared feature for feature with other languages.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In 1988, NeXT licensed Objective-C from StepStone (the new name of PPI, the owner of the Objective-C trademark) and extended the GCC compiler to support Objective-C.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] NeXT developed the Application Kit (AppKit) and Foundation Kit libraries on which the NeXTSTEP user interface and Interface Builder were based.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] While the NeXT workstations failed to make a great impact in the marketplace, the tools were widely lauded in the industry.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] NeXT dropped hardware production and focused on software tools, selling NeXTSTEP (and OPENSTEP) as a platform for custom programming.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] To circumvent the terms of the GPL, NeXT had originally intended to ship the Objective-C frontend separately, allowing the user to link it with GCC to produce the compiler executable.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Stallman, this plan was rejected after Stallman consulted with GNU's lawyers and NeXT agreed to make Objective-C part of GCC.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The work to extend GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) was led by Steve Naroff, who joined NeXT from StepStone.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The compiler changes were made available as per GNU General Public License (GPL) terms, but the runtime libraries were not, rendering the open source contribution unusable to the general public.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This led to other parties developing such runtime libraries under open source licenses.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Later, Steve Naroff was also principal contributor to work at Apple to build the Objective-C frontend to Clang.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The GNU project started work on its free software implementation of Cocoa, named GNUstep, based on the OpenStep standard.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Dennis Glatting wrote the first GNU Objective-C runtime in 1992.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The current GNU Objective-C runtime, in use since 1993, is the one developed by Kresten Krab Thorup while he was a university student in Denmark.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Thorup also worked at NeXT from 1993 to 1996.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] After acquiring NeXT in 1996, Apple Computer used OpenStep in its then-new operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This included Objective-C, NeXT's Objective-C-based developer tool, Project Builder, and its interface design tool, Interface Builder.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Both were later merged into one application, Xcode.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Most of Apple's current Cocoa API is based on OpenStep interface objects and is the most significant Objective-C environment being used for active development.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] At Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new language, Swift, which was characterized as "Objective-C without the C".
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C is a thin layer atop C and is a "strict superset" of C, meaning that it is possible to compile any C program with an Objective-C compiler and to freely include C language code within an Objective-C class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C derives its object syntax from Smalltalk.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] All of the syntax for non-object-oriented operations (including primitive variables, pre-processing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls) are identical to those of C, while the syntax for object-oriented features is an implementation of Smalltalk-style messaging.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The Objective-C model of object-oriented programming is based on message passing to object instances.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In Objective-C, one does not *call a method*; one *sends a message*.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This is unlike the Simula-style programming model used by C++.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The difference between these two concepts is in how the code referenced by the method or message name is executed.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In a Simula-style language, the method name is—in most cases—bound to a section of code in the target class by the compiler.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In Smalltalk and Objective-C, the target of a message is resolved at runtime, with the receiving object itself interpreting the message.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A method is identified by a *selector* or `SEL` — a unique identifier for each message name, often just a `NUL`-terminated string representing its name—and resolved to a C method pointer implementing it: an `IMP`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A consequence of this is that the message-passing system has no type checking.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The object to which the message is directed—the *receiver*—is not guaranteed to respond to a message, and if it does not, it raises an exception.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The "method" call is translated by the compiler to the `objc_msgSend(id self, SEL op, ...)` family of runtime functions.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Different implementations handle modern additions like `super`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In GNU families, this function is named `objc_msg_sendv`, but it has been deprecated in favor of a modern lookup system under `objc_msg_lookup`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Both styles of programming have multiple strengths and weaknesses.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Object-oriented programming in the Simula (C++) style allows multiple inheritance and faster execution by using compile-time binding whenever possible, but it does not support dynamic binding by default.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] It also forces all methods to have a corresponding implementation unless they are abstract.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The Smalltalk-style programming as used in Objective-C allows messages to go unimplemented, with the method resolved to its implementation at runtime.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] For example, a message may be sent to a collection of objects, to which only some will be expected to respond, without fear of producing runtime errors.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Message passing also does not require that an object be defined at compile time.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] An implementation is still required for the method to be called in the derived object.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C requires that the interface and implementation of a class be in separately declared code blocks.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] By convention, developers place the interface in a header file and the implementation in a code file.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The header files, normally suffixed .h, are similar to C header files while the implementation (method) files, normally suffixed .m, can be very similar to C code files.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This is analogous to class declarations as used in other object-oriented languages, such as C++ or Python.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The interface of a class is usually defined in a header file.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A common convention is to name the header file after the name of the class, e.g.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] `Ball.h` would contain the interface for the class `Ball`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above, plus signs denote class methods, or methods that can be called on the class itself (not on an instance), and minus signs denote instance methods, which can only be called on a particular instance of the class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Class methods also have no access to instance variables.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Note that `instanceMethod2With2Parameters:param2_callName:` demonstrates the interleaving of selector segments with argument expressions, for which there is no direct equivalent in C/C++.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Return types can be any standard C type, a pointer to a generic Objective-C object, a pointer to a specific type of object such as NSArray *, NSImage *, or NSString *, or a pointer to the class to which the method belongs (instancetype).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The default return type is the generic Objective-C type `id`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Method arguments begin with a name labeling the argument that is part of the method name, followed by a colon followed by the expected argument type in parentheses and the argument name.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A derivative of the interface definition is the *category*, which allows one to add methods to existing classes.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The interface only declares the class interface and not the methods themselves: the actual code is written in the implementation file.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Implementation (method) files normally have the file extension `.m`, which originally signified "messages".
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Methods are written using their interface declarations.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The syntax allows pseudo-naming of arguments.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Internal representations of a method vary between different implementations of Objective-C.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] If myColor is of the class `Color`, instance method `-changeColorToRed:green:blue:` might be internally labeled `_i_Color_changeColorToRed_green_blue`.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The `i` is to refer to an instance method, with the class and then method names appended and colons changed to underscores.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] As the order of parameters is part of the method name, it cannot be changed to suit coding style or expression as with true named parameters.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] However, internal names of the function are rarely used directly.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Generally, messages are converted to function calls defined in the Objective-C runtime library.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] It is not necessarily known at link time which method will be called because the class of the receiver (the object being sent the message) need not be known until runtime.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Once an Objective-C class is written, it can be instantiated.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This is done by first allocating an uninitialized instance of the class (an object) and then by initializing it.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] An object is not fully functional until both steps have been completed.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] These steps should be accomplished with one line of code so that there is never an allocated object that hasn't undergone initialization (and because it is unwise to keep the intermediate result since `-init` can return a different object than that on which it is called).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Also, some classes implement class method initializers.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Like `+new`, they combine `+alloc` and `-init`, but unlike `+new`, they return an autoreleased instance.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The *alloc* message allocates enough memory to hold all the instance variables for an object, sets all the instance variables to zero values, and turns the memory into an instance of the class; at no point during the initialization is the memory an instance of the superclass.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The *init* message performs the set-up of the instance upon creation.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above example, notice the `id` return type.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This type stands for *pointer to any object* in Objective-C (See the Dynamic typing section).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The initializer pattern is used to assure that the object is properly initialized by its superclass before the init method performs its initialization.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A non-valid object pointer has the value `nil`; conditional statements like `if` treat nil like a null pointer, so the initialization code will not be executed if `[super init]` returned nil.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] If there is an error in initialization, the init method should perform any necessary cleanup, including sending a `release` message to self, and return `nil` to indicate that initialization failed.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Any checking for such errors must only be performed after having called the superclass initialization to ensure that destroying the object will be done correctly.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] If a class has more than one initialization method, only one of them (the *designated initializer*) needs to follow this pattern; others should call the designated initializer instead of the superclass initializer.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In other programming languages, these are called *interfaces*.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C was extended at NeXT to introduce the concept of multiple inheritance of specification, but not implementation, through the introduction of protocols.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This is a pattern achievable either as an abstract multiple inherited base class in C++, or as an *interface* (as in Java and C#).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C makes use of ad hoc protocols called *informal protocols* and compiler-enforced protocols called *formal protocols*.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] An informal protocol is a list of methods that a class can opt to implement.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] It is specified in the documentation, since it has no presence in the language.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Informal protocols are implemented as a category (see below) on NSObject and often include optional methods, which, if implemented, can change the behavior of a class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] For example, a text field class might have a delegate that implements an informal protocol with an optional method for performing auto-completion of user-typed text.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The text field discovers whether the delegate implements that method (via reflective programming (reflection)) and, if so, calls the delegate's method to support the auto-complete feature.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A formal protocol is similar to an interface in Java, C#, and Ada 2005.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] It is a list of methods that any class can declare itself to implement.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C versions before 2.0 required that a class must implement all methods in a protocol it declares itself as adopting; the compiler will emit an error if the class does not implement every method from its declared protocols.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C 2.0 added support for marking certain methods in a protocol optional, and the compiler will not enforce implementation of optional methods.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] A class must be declared to implement that protocol to be said to conform to it.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Formal protocols cannot provide any implementations; they simply assure callers that classes that conform to the protocol will provide implementations.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the NeXT/Apple library, protocols are frequently used by the Distributed Objects system to represent the abilities of an object executing on a remote system.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] denotes that there is the abstract idea of locking.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] instances of NSLock claim that they will provide an implementation for the two instance methods.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C, like Smalltalk, can use dynamic typing: an object can be sent a message that is not specified in its interface.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This can allow for increased flexibility, as it allows an object to "capture" a message and send the message to a different object that can respond to the message appropriately, or likewise send the message on to another object.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This behavior is known as *message forwarding* or *delegation* (see below).
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Alternatively, an error handler can be used in case the message cannot be forwarded.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] If an object does not forward a message, respond to it, or handle an error, then the system will generate a runtime exception.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] If messages are sent to *nil* (the null object pointer), they will be silently ignored or raise a generic exception, depending on compiler options.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Static typing information may also optionally be added to variables.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This information is then checked at compile time.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the following four statements, increasingly specific type information is provided.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The statements are equivalent at runtime, but the extra information allows the compiler to warn the programmer if the passed argument does not match the type specified.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be of any class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be an instance of any class that conforms to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class, and it must conform to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] In Objective-C, all objects are represented as pointers, and static initialization is not allowed.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The simplest object is the type that id (objc_obj *) points to, which only has an *isa* pointer describing its class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Other types from C, like values and structs, are unchanged because they are not part of the object system.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] This decision differs from the C++ object model, where structs and classes are united.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Objective-C permits the sending of a message to an object that may not respond.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Rather than responding or simply dropping the message, an object can forward the message to an object that can respond.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Forwarding can be used to simplify implementation of certain design patterns, such as the observer pattern or the proxy pattern.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] An object wishing to implement forwarding needs only to override the forwarding method with a new method to define the forwarding behavior.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The action method `performv::` need not be overridden, as this method merely performs an action based on the selector and arguments.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Notice the `SEL` type, which is the type of messages in Objective-C.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Note: in OpenStep, Cocoa, and GNUstep, the commonly used frameworks of Objective-C, one does not use the `Object` class.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] The `- (void)forwardInvocation:(NSInvocation *)anInvocation` method of the `NSObject` class is used to do forwarding.
[src:core-foundation/objective-c] Here is an example of a program that demonstrates the basics of forwarding.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] In computer science, an **opaque data type** is a data type whose concrete data structure is not defined in an interface.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] This enforces information hiding, since its values can only be manipulated by calling subroutines that have access to the missing information.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] The concrete representation of the type is hidden from its users, and the visible implementation is incomplete.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] A data type whose representation is visible is called **transparent**.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Opaque data types are frequently used to implement abstract data types.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Typical examples of opaque data types include handles for resources provided by an operating system to application software.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] For example, the POSIX standard for threads defines an application programming interface based on a number of opaque types that represent threads or synchronization primitives like mutexes or condition variables.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] An opaque pointer is a special case of an opaque data type, a datatype that is declared to be a pointer to a record or data structure of some unspecified data type.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Some languages, such as C, allow the declaration of opaque records (structs), whose size and fields are hidden from the client.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] The only thing that the client can do with an object of such a type is to take its memory address, to produce an opaque pointer.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] If the information provided by the interface is sufficient to determine the type's size, then clients can declare variables, fields, and arrays of that type, assign their values, and possibly compare them for equality.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] This is usually the case for opaque pointers.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] In some languages, such as Java, the only kind of opaque type provided is the opaque pointer.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Indeed, in Java (and several other languages) records are always handled through pointers.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Some languages allow partially opaque types, e.g. a record which has some *public* fields, known and accessible to all clients, and some *hidden* fields which are not revealed in the interface.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] Such types play a fundamental role in object-oriented programming.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] The information which is missing in the interface may be declared in its implementation, or in another "friends-only" interface.
[src:core-foundation/opaque-data-type] This second option allows the hidden information to be shared by two or more modules.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In the macOS, iOS, NeXTSTEP, and GNUstep programming frameworks, **property list** files are files that store serialized objects.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Property list files use the filename extension `.plist`, and thus are often referred to as **p-list** files.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Property list files are often used to store a user's settings.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] They are also used to store information about bundles and applications, a task served by the resource fork in the old Mac OS.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Property lists are also used for localization strings for development.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] These files use the `.strings` or `.stringsdict` extensions.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The former is a "reduced" old-style plist containing only one dictionary without the braces (see propertyListFromStringsFileFormat), while the latter is a fully fledged plist.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Xcode also uses a `.pbxproj` extension for old-style plists used as project files.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Since the data represented by property lists is somewhat abstract, the underlying file format can be implemented in many ways.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Namely, NeXTSTEP used one format to represent a property list, and the subsequent GNUstep and macOS frameworks introduced differing formats.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Under NeXTSTEP, property lists were designed to be human-readable and edited by hand, serialized to ASCII in a syntax somewhat like a programming language.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] One limitation of the original NeXT property list format is that it could not represent an NSValue (number, Boolean, etc.) object.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] As a result, these values would have to be converted to string, and "fuzzily" recovered by the application.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Another limitation is that there is no official 8-bit encoding defined.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The defaults utility, introduced in OPENSTEP (1996), can be used to manipulate plist files used for storage of preferences (known as *defaults* in NeXTSTEP, hence the name) on the command line via their preferences domain, and this utility can be used to edit arbitrary plist files.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] This utility superseded three older commands (dread, dwrite, and dremove).
[src:core-foundation/property-list] GNUstep adopts the NeXTSTEP format, with additions for representing NSValue and NSDate data types.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The new typed entries have the form <**T*...>, where *T* is a one-letter type code.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] For example, an NSValue of Boolean YES is represented as <*BY> and NSDate objects are represented as `<*DYYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS +ZZZZ>`.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Binary data can also use the more efficient base64 format as <[ b64... ]>.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The 8-bit problem is implicitly solved as well, as most deployments use UTF-8.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] GNUstep also has its own binary format, NSPropertyListGNUstepBinaryFormat, implemented in NSSerialization.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] This format is defined recursively like the textual formats, with a single-byte type marker preceding some data.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] A form of string interning is supported via a GS-extension shouldBeCompact switch.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Two relative independent plist handlers are found in GNUstep: the CFPropertyList in libs-core-base (CoreFoundation), and the NSPropertyList in libs-base (Foundation Kit).
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Both support the binary and XML forms used by macOS to some degree, but the latter is a lot more complete.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] For example, the two GNUstep-specific formats are only handled in the latter.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] GNUstep provides a set of plist command-line tools based on NSPropertyList, including a version of pl and defaults.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] While macOS can also read the NeXTSTEP format, Apple sets it aside in favor of two new formats of its own, one XML-based and the other binary.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Apple also has a partially-compatible JSON format (NSJSONSerialization).
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In Mac OS X 10.0, the NeXTSTEP format was deprecated, and a new XML format was introduced, with a public DTD defined by Apple.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The XML format supports non-ASCII characters and storing NSValue objects (which, unlike GNUstep's ASCII property list format, Apple's ASCII property list format does not support).
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Since XML files, however, are not the most space-efficient means of storage, Mac OS X 10.2 introduced a new format where property list files are stored as binary files.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Starting with Mac OS X 10.4, this is the default format for preference files.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In Mac OS X 10.7, support for reading and writing files in JSON format was introduced.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] JSON and property lists are not fully compatible with each other, though.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] For example, property lists have native date and data types, which the JSON format does not support.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Conversely, JSON permits `null` values while property lists do not support explicit nulls.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The old defaults tool from NeXTSTEP remains available.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The /usr/libexec/PlistBuddy command provides an interactive plist editor.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The plutil utility (introduced in Mac OS X 10.2) can be used to check the syntax of property lists, or convert a property list file from one format to another.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] It also supports converting plists to Objective-C or Swift object literals.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Like the Cocoa NSPropertyListSerialization it is built on, it takes "old-style" inputs, but does not convert to this type.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The pl utility is introduced in Mac OS X v10.5.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] It takes any input and tries to generate "old-style" plists.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Like the GNUstep version, it appears to use the description property of Foundation types found in plists, which Apple has specified to produce valid old-style plists.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In terms of the internals, Apple provides an open source parser for old style, XML, and binary formats in their C Core Foundation code as CFPropertyList.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] However, all the utilities and most parts of the system use the closed-source NSPropertyList parser from the Obj-C Foundation Kit.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The Swift reimplementation is open source, but is not guaranteed to be identical.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] XML and JSON property lists are hand-editable in any text editor.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Additionally, Apple provides support in Xcode for editing property lists in a hierarchical viewer/editor that can handle plists formatted in binary or XML, but not JSON.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] As of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple provides an AppleScript interface for reading property list files through the System Events application.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] As of Mac OS X 10.5, Apple provides an AppleScript interface for editing, creating and writing property list files as well.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The binary file format is documented in a comment block in the Core Foundation C code source file (CF/CFBinaryPList.c) for Apple's open sourced implementation of binary plists in its Foundation library.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Apple describes the implementation as opaque in its plist(5) manual page documentation, which means that reliance on the format is discouraged.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In the binary file format the magic number (the first few bytes of the file which indicate that it's a valid plist file) is the text **bplist**, followed by two bytes indicating the version of the format.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The binary file can store some information that cannot be captured in the XML or JSON file formats.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The array, set and dictionary binary types are made up of **pointers** - the objref and keyref entries - that index into an object table in the file.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] This means that binary plists can capture the fact that - for example - a separate array and dictionary serialized into a file both have the same data element stored in them.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Converting such a binary file will result in a copy of the data element being placed into the XML file.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Additionally the binary file has a UID type that is used to identify data items when serialized.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] This means that the marker byte is only found in files with a format version no lower than the "1?" magic number.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The precise way to parse them is more nebulous than the way to parse legacy types, since the CFBinaryPlist implementation only handles version "0?".
[src:core-foundation/property-list] In practice, these types are never encountered, since NSKeyedArchiver is already capable of capturing these information.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] A table of offsets follow the object table, which is then followed by a trailer containing information on the size and location of the two tables.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Since property lists do not capture all the information and data types required to describe an arbitrary object, an extra layer of encoding and decoding is often done.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] The OpenStep specification abstracts the operation of serializing any NSObject under the NSCoding protocol.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Any class implementing this protocol can have its instances serialized by a NSCoder subclass to some other format.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Among other things, using an archiver allows for new datatypes to be encoded without changing the plist format itself and it is the preferred way for Apple to encode things like NSSets and null values.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Parsing the formats do prove a bit harder, since one more layer must be followed even for some classes plists were supposed to support.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Like the binary format which also has an object table, it is possible to create circular references in NSKeyedArchiver.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Since there is not a UID data type in XML, the integers are stored in a dictionary under the key "CF$UID".
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Apple publishes an open-source NSKeyedArchiver in Swift Corelibs Foundation; like the closed-source Apple Foundation, it restricts output formats to binary and XML only.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] It also has some test cases showing the results of serialization.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] GNUstep also has a compatible implementation, which does not limit output formats.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] There is not a single, standardized path language for property lists like XPath does for XML, but informal conventions used by various programs exist.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Neither format is able to express a key with the separator character in it.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Although best known on Apple or Darwin systems, including iOS and macOS, plist files are also present on Windows computers when Apple software, such as iTunes or Safari are installed.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] On Windows, the files are typically binary files, although some applications may generate PLIST files in the other formats.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] On Windows the Apple plist files are stored in the user's home directory under %USERPROFILE%\AppData\Roaming\Apple Computer.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] These plist files on Windows typically store preferences and other information, rather than using the Windows registry.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Options for editing PLIST files on Windows are not as extensive as on macOS.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] If the file is in the XML or JSON format with care a text editor such as Notepad++ can be used.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Apple ships a plutil.exe within its "Apple Application Support" package (which is part of iTunes), and it is identical to its macOS counterpart.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] Introduced in 2006 and first released with NetBSD#4.0 (2007) is a proplib library, which can be used for serialising data between the kernel and userland.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] It implements part of the XML plist language.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] One of the sample users of proplib is the second revision of the sysmon envsys framework for system monitoring.
[src:core-foundation/property-list] NetBSD's proplib library has also been ported to DragonFly in 2010, and is available since DragonFly BSD#2.8.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In computer science, **reference counting** is a programming technique of storing the number of references, pointers, or handles to a resource, such as an object, a block of memory, disk space, and others.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In garbage collection algorithms, reference counts may be used to deallocate objects that are no longer needed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The main advantage of the reference counting over tracing garbage collection is that objects are reclaimed *as soon as* they can no longer be referenced, and in an incremental fashion, without long pauses for collection cycles and with clearly defined lifetime of every object.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In real-time applications or systems with limited memory, this is important to maintain responsiveness.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counting is also among the simplest forms of memory management to implement.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It also allows for effective management of non-memory resources such as operating system objects, which are often much scarcer than memory (tracing garbage collection systems use finalizers for this, but the delayed reclamation may cause problems).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Weighted reference counts are a good solution for garbage collecting a distributed system.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Tracing garbage collection cycles are triggered too often if the set of live objects fills most of the available memory; it requires extra space to be efficient.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counting performance does not deteriorate as the total amount of free space decreases.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counts are also useful information to use as input to other runtime optimizations.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] For example, systems that depend heavily on immutable objects such as many functional programming languages can suffer an efficiency penalty due to frequent copies.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In addition to these, if the memory is allocated from a free list, reference counting suffers from poor locality.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counting alone cannot move objects to improve cache performance, so high performance collectors implement a tracing garbage collector as well.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Most implementations (such as the ones in PHP and Objective-C) suffer from poor cache performance since they do not implement copying objects.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When dealing with garbage collection schemes, it is often helpful to think of the **reference graph**, which is a directed graph where the vertices are objects and there is an edge from an object A to an object B if A holds a reference to B.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] We also have a special vertex or vertices representing the local variables and references held by the runtime system, and no edges ever go to these nodes, although edges can go from them to other nodes.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In this context, the simple reference count of an object is the in-degree of its vertex.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Deleting a vertex is like collecting an object.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It can only be done when the vertex has no incoming edges, so it does not affect the out-degree of any other vertices, but it can affect the in-degree of other vertices, causing their corresponding objects to be collected as well if their in-degree also becomes 0 as a result.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The connected component containing the special vertex contains the objects that can't be collected, while other connected components of the graph only contain garbage.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] If a reference-counting garbage collection algorithm is implemented, then each of these garbage components must contain at least one cycle; otherwise, they would have been collected as soon as their reference count (i.e., the number of incoming edges) dropped to zero.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Incrementing and decrementing reference counts every time a reference is created or destroyed can significantly impede performance.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Not only do the operations take time, but they damage cache performance and can lead to pipeline bubbles.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Even read-only operations like calculating the length of a list require a large number of reads and writes for reference updates with naive reference counting.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] One simple technique is for the compiler to combine a number of nearby reference updates into one.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This is especially effective for references which are created and quickly destroyed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Care must be taken, however, to put the combined update at the right position so that a premature free can be avoided.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It ignores these references, only counting references in data structures, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and registers that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Another technique devised by Henry Baker involves **deferred increments**, in which references which are stored in local variables do not immediately increment the corresponding reference count, but instead defer this until it is necessary.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] If such a reference is destroyed quickly, then there is no need to update the counter.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This eliminates a large number of updates associated with short-lived references (such as the above list-length-counting example).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] However, if such a reference is copied into a data structure, then the deferred increment must be performed at that time.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It is also critical to perform the deferred increment before the object's count drops to zero, to avoid a premature free.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] A dramatic decrease in the overhead on counter updates was obtained by Levanoni and Petrank.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] They introduce the **update coalescing method** which coalesces many of the redundant reference count updates.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It first points to an object `O1`, then to an object `O2`, and so forth until at the end of the interval it points to some object `On`.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In order to have the reference count properly evaluated at the end of the interval it is enough to perform `rc(O1)--` and `rc(On)++`.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Levanoni and Petrank showed in 2001 how to use such update coalescing in a reference counting collector.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When using update coalescing with an appropriate treatment of new objects, more than 99% of the counter updates are eliminated for typical Java benchmarks.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Interestingly, update coalescing also eliminates the need to employ atomic operations during pointer updates in a concurrent setting, this solving reference counting issues in a concurrent setting.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Therefore, update coalescing solves the third problem of naive reference counting (i.e., a costly overhead in a concurrent setting).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Levanoni and Petrank presented an enhanced algorithm that may run concurrently with multithreaded applications employing only fine synchronization.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Blackburn and McKinley's *ulterior reference counting* method in 2003 combines deferred reference counting with a copying nursery, observing that the majority of pointer mutations occur in young objects.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This algorithm achieves throughput comparable with the fastest generational copying collectors with the low bounded pause times of reference counting.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Perhaps the most obvious way to handle reference cycles is to design the system to avoid creating them.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] A system may explicitly forbid reference cycles; file systems with hard links often do this.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Judicious use of "weak" (non-counted) references may also help avoid retain cycles; the Cocoa framework, for instance, recommends using "strong" references for parent-to-child relationships and "weak" references for child-to-parent relationships.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Systems may also be designed to tolerate or correct the cycles they create in some way.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Developers may design code to explicitly "tear down" the references in a data structure when it is no longer needed, though this has the cost of requiring them to manually track that data structure's lifetime.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This technique can be automated by creating an "owner" object that does the tearing-down when it is destroyed; for instance, a Graph object's destructor could delete the edges of its GraphNodes, breaking the reference cycles in the graph.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Cycles may even be ignored in systems with short lives and a small amount of cyclic garbage, particularly when the system was developed using a methodology of avoiding cyclic data structures wherever possible, typically at the expense of efficiency.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Computer scientists have also discovered ways to detect and collect reference cycles automatically, without requiring changes in the data structure design.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] One simple solution is to periodically use a tracing garbage collector to reclaim cycles; since cycles typically constitute a relatively small amount of reclaimed space, the collector can be run much less often than with an ordinary tracing garbage collector.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Bacon describes a cycle-collection algorithm for reference counting with similarities to tracing collectors, including the same theoretical time bounds.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It is based on the observation that a cycle can only be isolated when a reference count is decremented to a nonzero value.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] All objects which this occurs on are put on a *roots* list, and then periodically the program searches through the objects reachable from the roots for cycles.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It knows it has found a cycle that can be collected when decrementing all the reference counts on a cycle of references brings them all down to zero.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] An enhanced version of this algorithm by Paz et al. is able to run concurrently with other operations and improve its efficiency by using the update coalescing method of Levanoni and Petrank.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Although it is possible to augment simple reference counts in a variety of ways, often a better solution can be found by performing reference counting in a fundamentally different way.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Here we describe some of the variants on reference counting and their benefits and drawbacks.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In weighted reference counting, each reference is assigned a *weight*, and each object tracks not the number of references referring to it, but the total weight of the references referring to it.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The initial reference to a newly created object has a large weight, such as 216.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Whenever this reference is copied, half of the weight goes to the new reference, and half of the weight stays with the old reference.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Since the total weight does not change, the object's reference count does not need to be updated.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Destroying a reference decrements the total weight by the weight of that reference.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When the total weight becomes zero, all references have been destroyed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] If an attempt is made to copy a reference with a weight of 1, the reference has to "get more weight" by adding to the total weight and then adding this new weight to the reference, and then splitting it.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] An alternative in this situation is to create an *indirection* reference object, the initial reference to which is created with a large weight which can then be split.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The property of not needing to access a reference count when a reference is copied is particularly helpful when the object's reference count is expensive to access, for example because it is in another process, on disk, or even across a network.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It can also help increase concurrency by avoiding many threads locking a reference count to increase it.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Thus, weighted reference counting is most useful in parallel, multiprocess, database, or distributed applications.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The primary problem with simple weighted reference counting is that destroying a reference still requires accessing the reference count, and if many references are destroyed, this can cause the same bottlenecks we seek to avoid.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Some adaptations of weighted reference counting seek to avoid this by transferring weight from a dying reference to an active reference.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Weighted reference counting was independently devised by Bevan and Watson & Watson in 1987.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In indirect reference counting, it is necessary to keep track of the reference's source.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This means that two references are kept to the object: a direct one which is used for invocations; and an indirect one which forms part of a diffusion tree, such as in the Dijkstra–Scholten algorithm, which allows a garbage collector to identify dead objects.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This approach prevents an object from being discarded prematurely.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] As a collection algorithm, reference counting tracks, for each object, a count of the number of references to it held by other objects.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] If an object's reference count reaches zero, the object has become inaccessible, and can be destroyed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When an object is destroyed, any objects referenced by that object also have their reference counts decreased.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Because of this, removing a single reference can potentially lead to a large number of objects being freed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] A common modification allows reference counting to be made incremental: instead of destroying an object as soon as its reference count becomes zero, it is added to a list of unreferenced objects, and periodically (or as needed) one or more items from this list are destroyed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Simple reference counts require frequent updates.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Whenever a reference is destroyed or overwritten, the reference count of the object it references is decremented, and whenever one is created or copied, the reference count of the object it references is incremented.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counting is also used in file systems and distributed systems, where full non-incremental tracing garbage collection is too time-consuming because of the size of the object graph and slow access speed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM) and WinRT makes pervasive use of reference counting.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In fact, two of the three methods that all COM objects must provide (in the IUnknown interface) increment or decrement the reference count.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Much of the Windows Shell and many Windows applications (including MS Internet Explorer, MS Office, and countless third-party products) are built on COM, demonstrating the viability of reference counting in large-scale systems.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] One primary motivation for reference counting in COM is to enable interoperability across different programming languages and runtime systems.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] A client need only know how to invoke object methods in order to manage object life cycle; thus, the client is completely abstracted from whatever memory allocator the implementation of the COM object uses.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] As a typical example, a Visual Basic program using a COM object is agnostic towards whether that object was allocated (and must later be deallocated) by a C++ allocator or another Visual Basic component.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] C++ does not perform reference-counting by default, fulfilling its philosophy of not adding functionality that might incur overheads where the user has not explicitly requested it.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Objects that are shared but not owned can be accessed via a reference, raw pointer, or iterator (a conceptual generalisation of pointers).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] However, by the same token, C++ provides native ways for users to opt-into such functionality: C++11 provides reference counted smart pointers, via the `std::shared_ptr` class, enabling automatic shared memory-management of dynamically allocated objects.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Programmers can use this in conjunction with weak pointers (via `std::weak_ptr`) to break cyclic dependencies.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Objects that are dynamically allocated but not intended to be shared can have their lifetime automatically managed using a `std::unique_ptr`.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In addition, C++11's move semantics further reduce the extent to which reference counts need to be modified by removing the deep copy normally used when a function returns an object, as it allows for a simple copy of the pointer of said object.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Apple's Cocoa and Cocoa Touch frameworks (and related frameworks, such as Core Foundation) use manual reference counting, much like COM.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Traditionally this was accomplished by the programmer manually sending `retain` and `release` messages to objects, but Automatic Reference Counting, a Clang compiler feature that automatically inserts these messages as needed, was added in iOS 5 and Mac OS X 10.7.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Mac OS X 10.5 introduced a tracing garbage collector as an alternative to reference counting, but it was deprecated in OS X 10.8 and removed from the Objective-C runtime library in macOS Sierra. iOS has never supported a tracing garbage collector.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It is up to the programmer to decide whether to use the built-in types; Delphi programmers have complete access to low-level memory management like in C/C++.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] So all potential cost of Delphi's reference counting can, if desired, be easily circumvented.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The GObject object-oriented programming framework implements reference counting on its base types, including weak references.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference incrementing and decrementing uses atomic operations for thread safety.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] A significant amount of the work in writing bindings to GObject from high-level languages lies in adapting GObject reference counting to work with the language's own memory management system.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The Vala programming language uses GObject reference counting as its primary garbage collection system, along with copy-heavy string handling.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Perl also uses reference counting, without any special handling of circular references, although (as in Cocoa and C++ above), Perl does support weak references, which allows programmers to avoid creating a cycle.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] PHP uses a reference counting mechanism for its internal variable management.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Since PHP 5.3, it implements the algorithm from Bacon's above mentioned paper.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] PHP allows you to turn on and off the cycle collection with user-level functions.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] It also allows you to manually force the purging mechanism to be run.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Python also uses reference counting and offers cycle detection as well (and can reclaim reference cycles).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Like other low-level languages, Rust does not provide reference counting by default.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Instead, any constructed type will be dropped when it falls out of scope.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When a programmer needs to define the scope of a constructed type, they often use lifetimes.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] However, the language also offers various alternatives to complex forms of memory management.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Reference counting functionality is provided by the `Rc` and `Arc` types, which are non-atomic and atomic respectively.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] For example, the type `Rc<T>` provides shared ownership of a value of type `T`, allocated on the heap for multiple references to its data.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Using these constructs allows programmers to avoid lifetimes for a small runtime cost.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Both reference counters keep track of the number of owners, as they must drop themselves when no owners remain.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] One noteworthy facet of these types is related to their usage as a shared reference.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] In Rust, shared references cannot mutate their held data, so `Rc` often comes bundled with `Cell`, and `Arc` with `Mutex`, in contexts where interior mutability is necessary.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Interior mutability without `UnsafeCell` has performance costs, too, so, for maximum performance, some applications may call for additional complexity.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Squirrel uses reference counting with cycle detection.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] This tiny language is relatively unknown outside the video game industry; however, it is a concrete example of how reference counting can be practical and efficient (especially in realtime environments).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Swift uses reference counting to track and manage the memory of class instances, and provides the `weak` keyword for creating weak references.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Instances of value types do not use reference counting.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Tcl 8 uses reference counting for memory management of values (Tcl Obj structs).
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Since Tcl's values are immutable, reference cycles are impossible to form and no cycle detection scheme is needed.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Operations that would replace a value with a modified copy are generally optimized to instead modify the original when its reference count indicates that it is not shared.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] The references are counted at a data structure level, so the problems with very frequent updates discussed above do not arise.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Xojo also uses reference counting, without any special handling of circular references, although (as in Cocoa and C++ above), Xojo does support weak references, which allows programmers to avoid creating a cycle.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] Many file systems maintain reference counts to any particular block or file, for example the inode *link count* on Unix-style file systems, which are usually known as hard links.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] When the count reaches zero, the file can be safely deallocated.
[src:core-foundation/reference-counting] While references can still be made from directories, some Unixes only allow references from live processes, and there can be files that exist outside the file system hierarchy.
